                    <h3>Our Heritage</h3>
                    <p>The pottery tradition of Kutch is one of the oldest craft forms of India, dating back to the Indus Valley Civilization. For generations, the Kumbhar community has been creating beautiful terracotta products using traditional techniques passed down through families.</p>
                    
                    <h3>Our Artisans</h3>
                    <p>Our products are handcrafted by skilled artisans from villages like Khavda and Lodai in the Kutch region of Gujarat. Each piece is made using locally sourced clay and traditional techniques that have remained unchanged for centuries.</p>
                    
                    <h3>Our Process</h3>
                    <p>Traditional pottery in Kutch involves a meticulous process:</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Clay Preparation: Local clay is collected, cleaned, and prepared for molding.</li>
                        <li>Wheel Work: Potters use a foot-operated wheel (chak) to shape the clay into various forms.</li>
                        <li>Sun Drying: The shaped pieces are dried in the sun.</li>
                        <li>Decoration: Artisans apply natural pigments and create intricate patterns using techniques like sgraffito.</li>
                        <li>Firing: The pieces are fired in traditional kilns at high temperatures.</li>
                        <li>Finishing: Some pieces receive a food-safe glaze before a final firing.</li>
                    </ol>
                    
                    <h3>Our Mission</h3>
                    <p>At Pottery of Kutch, our mission is to preserve and promote the rich pottery tradition of the Kutch region while providing sustainable livelihoods for the artisan communities. By bringing these beautiful handcrafted products to a global audience, we aim to ensure that this ancient craft continues to thrive for generations to come.</p>
